  <h1>Cybersecurity Newsfeed</h1>
  <h2>📅 16/03/26</h2>

  <h2>🛡️ Vulnerabilities</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Microsoft Issues OOB Hotpatch for Windows 11 RCE</strong>: Microsoft released an out-of-band (OOB) hotpatch, KB5084597, to address a critical remote code execution (RCE) vulnerability in the Windows Routing and Remote Access Service (RRAS). The flaw affects Windows 11 versions 24H2 and 25H2. An attacker could exploit this by tricking a management tool into connecting to a malicious server. The hotpatch installs automatically without requiring a system reboot. <a href="https://www.bleepingcomputer.com/news/microsoft/microsoft-releases-windows-11-oob-hotpatch-to-fix-rras-rce-flaw/" target="_blank">More info</a></li>

    <li><strong>CrackArmor Vulnerabilities Expose Linux AppArmor Deficiencies</strong>: Researchers at Qualys disclosed "CrackArmor," a collection of nine vulnerabilities in the Linux kernel's AppArmor module. These "confused deputy" flaws allow unprivileged users to manipulate security profiles, leading to local privilege escalation and container isolation bypass. Immediate kernel patching is required for affected Ubuntu and Debian systems. <a href="https://hackread.com/crackarmor-vulnerability-apparmor-linux-systems/" target="_blank">More info</a></li>

    <li><strong>Cisco Warns of Fake PoCs and SD-WAN Zero-Day</strong>: A critical zero-day in Cisco Catalyst SD-WAN Manager (CVE-2026-20127) has been exploited for at least three years, allowing high-privileged access. Simultaneously, fake PoC exploits on GitHub are delivering malware to researchers. CISA has added the flaw to its Known Exploited Vulnerabilities catalog. <a href="https://www.darkreading.com/vulnerabilities-threats/fake-pocs-risks-cisco-sd-wan" target="_blank">More info</a></li>

    <li><strong>Google Patches Two Exploited Zero-Days in Chrome 146</strong>: Google released an emergency update to address CVE-2026-3909 and CVE-2026-3910, which are being actively exploited. The flaws involve out-of-bounds write in the Skia library and improper implementation in the V8 engine, potentially leading to arbitrary code execution via malicious websites. <a href="https://www.securityweek.com/chrome-146-update-patches-two-exploited-zero-days/" target="_blank">More info</a></li>

    <li><strong>SQL Injection Vulnerability Found in Ally WordPress Plugin</strong>: A critical SQL injection vulnerability (CVE-2026-2413) was found in the Elementor Ally accessibility plugin, affecting over 400,000 sites. Unauthenticated attackers can extract sensitive database information, including password hashes. Administrators are urged to update to version 4.0.4 immediately. <a href="https://hackread.com/sql-injection-vulnerability-ally-wordpress-plugin/" target="_blank">More info</a></li>
  </ul>

  <h2>🎯 Adversaries</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Payload Ransomware Targets Royal Bahrain Hospital</strong>: The Payload ransomware group has claimed a cyberattack on the Royal Bahrain Hospital. Threat actors allege they have successfully exfiltrated sensitive information from internal systems. Hospital authorities are currently assessing the impact on patient records and service continuity. <a href="https://securityaffairs.com/189467/cyber-crime/payload-ransomware-claims-the-hack-of-royal-bahrain-hospital.html" target="_blank">More info</a></li>

    <li><strong>AiTM Phishing Hijacks AWS Accounts via Typosquatting</strong>: An adversary-in-the-middle (AiTM) campaign is targeting AWS admins using spoofed security alerts and typosquatted domains. The kit captures credentials, MFA tokens, and session cookies in real time, often leading to unauthorized logins within 20 minutes of the initial phishing lure. <a href="https://www.helpnetsecurity.com/2026/03/15/week-in-review-aitm-phishing-kit-used-to-hijack-aws-accounts-year-long-malware-campaign-targets-hr/" target="_blank">More info</a></li>

    <li><strong>Glassworm Exploits Unicode for Supply Chain Attacks</strong>: The Glassworm actor has compromised over 150 repositories across GitHub, npm, and VS Code Marketplace using invisible Unicode characters. These payloads evade standard code review tools to fetch second-stage malware capable of stealing credentials and cryptocurrency. <a href="https://thehackernews.com/2026/03/glassworm-supply-chain-attack-abuses-72.html" target="_blank">More info</a></li>

    <li><strong>Storm-2561 Distributes Trojanized VPN Clients</strong>: Threat actor Storm-2561 is luring victims to spoofed enterprise VPN download pages. These sites deliver trojanized installers that appear functional but contain malware designed to steal corporate login credentials and session tokens from remote workers. <a href="https://thehackernews.com/2026/03/storm-2561-spreads-trojan-vpn-clients.html" target="_blank">More info</a></li>

    <li><strong>PixRevolution Trojan Hijacks Brazilian Instant Payments</strong>: A sophisticated Android trojan named PixRevolution is targeting Brazil’s PIX system. Using an "agent-in-the-loop" model, it monitors the victim's screen in real time and secretly alters recipient details during transfers, bypassing the irrevocability of PIX transactions. <a href="https://www.darkreading.com/application-security/real-time-banking-trojan-strikes-brazils-pix-users" target="_blank">More info</a></li>
  </ul>

  <h2>📈 Trends</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Slopoly Malware Employs AI for Ransomware Campaigns</strong>: The Hive0163 group is utilizing Slopoly, a new AI-assisted malware variant. It leverages AI to generate polymorphic code and craft convincing phishing lures, representing a significant escalation in the technical capabilities of ransomware affiliates. <a href="https://securityaffairs.com/189378/malware/ai-assisted-slopoly-malware-powers-hive0163s-ransomware-campaigns.html" target="_blank">More info</a></li>

    <li><strong>Betterleaks Emerges as Successor to Gitleaks</strong>: Developer Zach Rice has introduced Betterleaks, an open-source secrets scanner. Utilizing Byte Pair Encoding tokenization rather than entropy-based detection, it reportedly achieves 98.6% recall in identifying credentials across Git repositories. <a href="https://www.bleepingcomputer.com/news/security/betterleaks-a-new-open-source-secrets-scanner-to-replace-gitleaks/" target="_blank">More info</a></li>

    <li><strong>Scammers Impersonate Malwarebytes in Calendar Spam</strong>: A new social engineering campaign utilizes fake calendar invitations to impersonate Malwarebytes renewal notices. This "vishing" tactic aims to trick victims into calling a fraudulent number to provide credit card details or grant remote access. <a href="https://www.malwarebytes.com/blog/threat-intel/2026/03/fake-malwarebytes-renewal-notices-in-your-calendar" target="_blank">More info</a></li>
  </ul>

  <h2>💥 Breaches & Leaks</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>ShinyHunters Claims Massive 1PB Telus Digital Breach</strong>: The ShinyHunters group claims to have exfiltrated one petabyte of data from Telus Digital. Allegedly stolen data includes customer support recordings, proprietary source code, and employee records containing FBI background check results. Telus has confirmed unauthorized access. <a href="https://hackread.com/shinyhunters-1-petabyte-data-breach-telus-digital/" target="_blank">More info</a></li>

    <li><strong>AppsFlyer SDK Compromised in Supply Chain Attack</strong>: The AppsFlyer JavaScript Web SDK was compromised, injecting malicious code into websites using the script. The malware intercepts authentication tokens and payment info. Organizations are recommended to block the script until a clean version is verified. <a href="https://www.bleepingcomputer.com/news/security/appsflyer-web-sdk-used-to-spread-crypto-stealer-javascript-code/" target="_blank">More info</a></li>

    <li><strong>Loblaw Data Breach Exposes Customer Contact Information</strong>: Canadian retailer Loblaw confirmed a breach involving a third-party actor. Basic customer info including names and phone numbers was exposed, though sensitive data like credit cards and health records were reportedly not compromised. <a href="https://www.securityweek.com/loblaw-data-breach-impacts-customer-information/" target="_blank">More info</a></li>

    <li><strong>Starbucks Discloses Breach Affecting Employee Data</strong>: A phishing campaign targeting Starbucks’ internal employee portal compromised "Partner Central" accounts. The breach exposed sensitive staff info for 889 employees. Starbucks has since secured the accounts and provided support to those affected. <a href="https://securityaffairs.com/189438/security/starbucks-data-breach-impacts-889-employees.html" target="_blank">More info</a></li>
  </ul>

  <h2>📚 Others</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Interpol Dismantles 45,000 Malicious IPs</strong>: Operation Synergia III, involving 72 countries, resulted in the dismantling of 45,000 malicious IPs and 94 arrests. The crackdown targeted global infrastructure used for phishing, ransomware, and banking malware. <a href="https://securityaffairs.com/189420/cyber-crime/interpol-operation-synergia-iii-leads-to-45000-malicious-ips-dismantled-and-94-arrests-worldwide.html" target="_blank">More info</a></li>

    <li><strong>Poland's Nuclear Research Centre Targeted by Cyberattack</strong>: The National Centre for Nuclear Research (NCBJ) blocked a cyberattack targeting its IT infrastructure. While reactor operations remained safe, indicators potentially link the activity to Iranian threat actors. <a href="https://www.bleepingcomputer.com/news/security/polands-nuclear-research-centre-targeted-by-cyberattack/" target="_blank">More info</a></li>

    <li><strong>Security Affairs Newsletter Round 567 Overview</strong>: Highlights include French arrests in a $46M crypto theft, a $2.7M exploit in Solv Protocol, and India's detention of a CTO linked to the GainBitcoin Ponzi scheme. <a href="https://securityaffairs.com/189451/breaking-news/security-affairs-newsletter-round-567-by-pierluigi-paganini-international-edition.html" target="_blank">More info</a></li>
  </ul>

